            {
              "__typename": "IssueComment",
              "id": "IC_kwDOFcwZ1c5jzNV4",
              "createdAt": "2023-08-11T08:14:57Z",
              "body": "Do people ever consider FLT with other coefficients?\r\n\r\nFor example do we care about this sort of thing: https://math.stackexchange.com/questions/3701758/fermats-last-theorem-for-entire-functions\r\n\r\nIf so we might want to generalise the coefficients and change `0 < a` into `a ≠ 0` (likewise `b`). Also apparently for the ring of entire functions the critical exponent is not `2 < n` but `3 < n`. Should we care about this sort of thing?\r\n\r\nAre there any easy enough interesting coefficients where we can prove / disprove it that could be included as part of this PR?",
              "author": {
                "login": "ocfnash"
              }
            },
            {
              "__typename": "IssueComment",
              "id": "IC_kwDOFcwZ1c5j0yVV",
              "createdAt": "2023-08-11T13:16:58Z",
              "body": "n = 4 is already in mathlib",
              "author": {
                "login": "Ruben-VandeVelde"
              }
            },
            {
              "__typename": "IssueComment",
              "id": "IC_kwDOFcwZ1c5j1BNW",
              "createdAt": "2023-08-11T14:00:09Z",
              "body": "What's the motivation for adding such statements to mathlib. To me it seems Riemann is interesting as a demo that we have a proper definition of zeta, and likewise BSD would be interesting as a statement for a similar reason.",
              "author": {
                "login": "alexjbest"
              }
            },
            {
              "__typename": "IssueComment",
              "id": "IC_kwDOFcwZ1c5j1LZ1",
              "createdAt": "2023-08-11T14:27:04Z",
              "body": "Alex: the PR was really an attempt to discover whether the reason we have RH is because it is a famous mathematical problem or because we want to demonstrate that we have the tools to state it formally. Note that I am totally open-minded about whether this PR gets merged: it was just a Friday night idea. I totally agree that there is a far stronger case for BSD to be included.\r\n\r\nOliver: x^n+y^n=z^n is a smooth projective curve and it makes sense to ask about its solutions over many fields, as of course you know. If you change the field then you change the question, and for some fields the answer is simple and for others it's complicated. The n=3 case is interesting because it is the point where the Euler characteristic changes from positive to negative; this topological invariant controls the arithmetic of the curve, but when the characteristic is 0 whether you get finitely many or infinitely many solutions depends also on the arithmetic of the field; for example there are many number fields where x^3+y^3=z^3 has infinitely many projective points. For function fields I should think that there is certainly potential for a PR.",
              "author": {
                "login": "kbuzzard"
              }
            },
            {
              "__typename": "IssueComment",
              "id": "IC_kwDOFcwZ1c5j1NaK",
              "createdAt": "2023-08-11T14:33:10Z",
              "body": "Thanks for the thoughtful response!\r\n\r\nI'm also opened-minded about whether we should add this. However I would add that a point in favour of the RH which FLT does not have, is that there are lots of interesting mathematical theorems of the form \"RH => x\". It makes sense to have a standard form of RH in order to state these consistently.",
              "author": {
                "login": "ocfnash"
              }
            },
            {
              "__typename": "IssueComment",
              "id": "IC_kwDOFcwZ1c5j1Rmq",
              "createdAt": "2023-08-11T14:46:22Z",
              "body": "If we do add this I'm pretty sure it doesn't belong in `Data/Nat/Basic`!",
              "author": {
                "login": "eric-wieser"
              }
            },
            {
              "__typename": "IssueComment",
              "id": "IC_kwDOFcwZ1c5j1Ru7",
              "createdAt": "2023-08-11T14:46:45Z",
              "body": "> We've got the statement of the Riemann Hypothesis.\r\n\r\nCan you link to that?",
              "author": {
                "login": "eric-wieser"
              }
            },
            {
              "__typename": "IssueComment",
              "id": "IC_kwDOFcwZ1c5j1gmw",
              "createdAt": "2023-08-11T15:26:00Z",
              "body": "https://leanprover-community.github.io/mathlib4_docs/Mathlib/NumberTheory/ZetaFunction.html#RiemannHypothesis",
              "author": {
                "login": "Ruben-VandeVelde"
              }
            },
            {
              "__typename": "CrossReferencedEvent",
              "id": "CRE_kwDOFcwZ1c5OGJY9",
